subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis
: 
Phylinae
elongate and rather flat dorsally. Tegument shiny. Vestiture consisting of long, erect, black setae, arising from dark spots. Antennae robust but not incrassate. Calli of pronotum strongly marked, both structurally and chromatically, and delimited by dark spots. Mesothoracic spiracle and metasternal scent gland as in 
Fig. 3
. Hemelytral membrane greyish with whitish veins. Femora spotted. Tibial spines black, arising from dark spots. Claws (
Fig. 1
) robust, strongly bent medially with the apical part nearly straight and the basal part conspicuously wide; pulvillus large but narrow, largely joined to the basal part of the claw. Male genitalia: pygophore (
Fig. 2
) very long; right paramere (
Fig. 5
) rectilinear, with a basal protuberance; left paramere (
Fig. 6
) with sensory lobe short and blunt; vesica (
Fig. 7
) “J”-shaped with lateral torsion, composed of two thick strands ending in two apical points forming a sub-right angle, with the secondary gonopore in subapical position. Female genitalia: dorsal wall of the genital chamber (
Fig. 8
) sub-oval, with sclerotized rings sub-triangular and dorsal sac protruding dorso-posteriorly; vestibulum greatly developed, particularly to the right side (
Figs. 8–9
); posterior wall present (
Fig. 10
).
